T*
(pg_restore_relation_stats\(\) and pg_restore_attribute_stats\(\) functions that were introduced in) Tj
T*
(PostgreSQL 18 in September 2025. The PostgreSQL query planner makes use of internal statistics) Tj
T*
(to help it decide how to best execute a query. These statistics often differ between production) Tj
T*
(data and development environments, which means the query plans used in production may not be) Tj
T*
(replicable in development. PostgreSQL's new features now let you copy those statistics down to) Tj
T*
(your development environment, allowing you to simulate the plans for production workloads) Tj
T*
(without needing to copy in all of that data first. I found this illustrative example useful:) Tj
T*
(SELECT pg_restore_attribute_stats\( 'schemaname', 'public', 'relname', 'test_orders', 'attname',) Tj
T*
('status', 'inherited', false::boolean, 'null_frac', 0.0::real, 'avg_width', 9::integer,) Tj
T*
('n_distinct', 5::real, 'most_common_vals',) Tj
T*
('{delivered,shipped,cancelled,pending,returned}'::text, 'most_common_freqs',) Tj
T*
('{0.95,0.015,0.015,0.015,0.005}'::real[] \); This simulates statistics for a status column that) Tj
T*
(is 95% delivered . Based on these statistics PostgreSQL can decide...) Tj
